ng through the convertor table properties to ensure nothing is missing. ✓, SystemChar ✓, SystemCharValidator ✓ - those annotations and classes are all accounted for. Looking through the s3 and s4 sections, the charset-related classes and their properties like startCodePoint, endCodePoint, and the various charsetDef references are covered, along with the messageId property and @SystemChar annotation. The hints appear comprehensive across all sections.\n\nNow I'm doing a careful check against the original V1 documentation to catch anything I might have missed. The cross-references to BigDecimalConvertor, IntegerConvertor, and LongConvertor are just pointing to external docs, so those are fine to skip. There's also a footnote about defining character sets that gets cut off, but it looks like it's just an example of how to construct a specific charset definition.\n\nThe images referenced in the source can't be included in a text knowledge file anyway, so those are acceptable omissions. There's another note about LiteralCharsetDef that also appears to be cut off, but it seems to be explaining a simplification made in the documentation for clarity.\n\nLooking at the next part about CompositeCharsetDef, the ordering of code points matters—the validation checks them in the order they're listed in the configuration. So if certain character sets appear more frequently in the system, placing them earlier in the list would be more efficient. ただし、文字の種類が多く出現頻度にばらつきがない場合は、順序の最適化だけでは性能が不十分になることもある。そうした場合、判定結果をキャッシュすることで性能を改善でき、特に処理時間の変動を抑えたいときに効果的だ。\n\nSystemCharValidatorのメッセージIDはデフォルトとして機能するため、@SystemCharとCharsetDefにメッセージID指定がない場合に使用されることになり、必ず指定する必要がある。\n\n定義した許容文字集合をSystemCharValidatorに設定することで、@SystemCharアノテーションによるシステム許容文字チェックが実施できるようになる。\n\nConfiguring the validator component... I'm checking the source documentation against the knowledge file to verify accuracy. The source explains that character set validation happens in list order, so placing frequently-used character sets first improves performance—the knowledge file captures this correctly but more concisely. I'm also tracking a section count discrepancy that needs investigation. I'm verifying the `@Digits` annotation details across the converters—the source mentions it's required for IntegerConvertor and LongConvertor with a reference to BigDecimalConvertor's section, and the knowledge file correctly captures that all three require it. The cross-reference in the Japanese note is just pointing to an already-documented section, so that checks out. I've now reviewed the content thoroughly and the knowledge file appears complete with no significant gaps, despite what the automated section count suggested. I'm verifying the LengthValidator details match between source and knowledge file - the note about length-0 strings being handled by @Required is correctly captured. Now let me double-check the V4 hints against the first table in the source to make sure everything aligns. I'm noticing a minor discrepancy where \"システム許容文字チェック\" isn't explicitly in the hints but SystemCharValidator is present, though the s2 section does reference \"システム許容文字\" so it's close enough. The source also mentions standard Java types like String and BigDecimal as conversion targets, which appear in the table but not the hints—though these are just standard library classes rather than domain-specific terms. Overall, the knowledge file looks consistent.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":24804,"cache_read_input_tokens":29807,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":24804,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c3256cd2-e4a4-4db0-ad57-ce8e9dec06d8","uuid":"61bb5ff3-0508-4a66-8394-a1067840c684"}
